{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὕπαιθρ-ος</b>, ον, <br /> = {ὑπαίθριος}, [κοίτη] [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ διαίτης ὀξέων” 45 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἱππεῖς καὶ στρατιῶται, i.e. encamped, opposed to κάτοικοι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “OGI” 229.14 (Smyrna, 3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; ἔδοξεν Ἀθηναίων τοῖς τεταγμένοις ἐν Ἐλευσῖνι.. καὶ τοῖς ὑπαίθροις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 22.1304.3 (3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; παραχειμασία [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 3.87.2; δυνάμεις [prev. author] 1.82.14, compare “PCair.Zen.” 545.5 (3rd c.BC), “PMich.Zen.” 90.3 (3rd c.BC), “PTeb.” 722.11 (2nd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; τὰ κτήνη μου ὕ. ἐστιν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “PEnteux.” 11.2 (3rd c.BC)\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; ἀγῶνες [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 2.108S.; πόλεμοι 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 6.22; ὕπαιθρον ὕλην λεῖπε 2nd c.AD: Babrius Fabularum Scriptor 12.14. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>public, open,</b> ὑ. πράξεσι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Cat.Ma.” 16; παραφροσύνην ὕ. [prev. author] “Agis” 2. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> as <i>substantive</i>, ὕπαιθρον, τό, <b>open enclosure,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Inscriptiones Graecae 22.1035.47, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Symp.” 20 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; ἐν ὑπαίθρῳ in <b>the open air,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.11, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Memorabilia” 2.1.6, “Oec.” 7.19: _metaphorically_, εἰς ὕπαιθρον\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] into <b>the public view,</b> into <b>the daylight,</b> πρῶτον εἰς ὕ. ἐξεληλυθώς, of a youth,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Pib. 10.3.4; εἰς ὕ. ἕλκειν τινά 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.501d; τὴν αὑτῶν ἀμαθίαν εἰς ὕ. ἄγουσι 1st c.AD: Erotianus Grammaticus “Prooem.” \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> in military language, from [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus downwards, τὰ ὕ.\">Refs 2nd c.BC+</a>] the <b>field,</b> the <b>open country,</b> opposed to fortified places, τῶν ὑ. ἀντιποιεῖσθαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.12.4, 1.30.6; μάχεσθαι ἐν τοῖς ὑ. 18.3.4 \">Refs</a>]; ἐκχωρεῖν τῶν ὑ. retire from the <b>open country,</b> and shut themselves up in the towns,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 9.3.6; ἡ ἐν ὑπαίθροις οἰκονομία 6.12.5. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> ἡ ὕπαιθρος (i.e. γῆ(, ={τὰ ὕπαιθρα}, the <b>field,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 8.63, 9.6. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> <b>open to the sky,</b> Latin <i>hypaethros, aedificia, ambulationes,</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Vitruvius Scriptor de Architectura Latinus 1.2.5, 5.9.5\">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; <b>hypaethros</b> (i.e. ναός), <b>a temple with an open skylight,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 3.2.1. This form is not used by _Attic dialect_ writers except in the phrase ἐν ὑπαίθρῳ\">Refs</a>]; the form employed by them in <i>adjective</i> sense is always ὑπαίθριο; see [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 7.20, where αἱ ἐν τῷ ὑπαίθρῳ ἐργασίαι are synonymous with ὑπαίθρια ἔργα. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G9537","accentedUnicode":"ὕπαιθρος","shortDef":"open air","mediumDef":"open air","stepGloss":"open air","stepTransliteration":"hupaithros","_step_Type":"word"}]}